To write a function that converts Markdown to HTML, you would typically need to implement a full Markdown parser, which can be quite complex due to the variety of Markdown features (headings, lists, code blocks, links, images, etc.). However, I can provide you with a simple example function that handles a few basic Markdown features, such as headings, bold text, and italics.

Here is a basic implementation in C++:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(std::string &markdown) {
    std::string html = markdown;

    // Convert Markdown headings to HTML
    std::regex headingRegex("^#{1,6}\\s*(.+)$", std::regex_constants::multiline);
    html = std::regex_replace(html, headingRegex, "<h$1>$2</h$1>");

    // Convert Markdown bold to HTML (double asterisks or double underscores)
    std::regex boldRegex("\\*\\*(.*?)\\*\\*|__(.*?)__");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, boldRegex, "<strong>$1$2</strong>");

    // Convert Markdown italics to HTML (single asterisks or single underscores)
    std::regex italicsRegex("\\*(.*?)\\*|_(.*?)_");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, italicsRegex, "<em>$1$2</em>");

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdownText = "# Heading\nThis is **bold** and this is *italic*.";
    std::string htmlText = markdownToHtml(markdownText);
    std::cout << htmlText << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This function uses regular expressions to find and replace Markdown syntax with the corresponding HTML tags. Keep in mind that this function is very basic and does not handle all Markdown features. It also assumes the input Markdown text is well-formed and does not include edge cases or error handling.

